From Jungclas Subject Re Big amateur rockets In article Paul Dokas writes I was reading Popular Science this morning and was surprised by an ad in the I know that a lot of the ads in the back of PS are fringe science or questionablely legal but this one really grabbed my It was from a company name Personal Missle or something like Anyhow the ad stated that they'd sell rockets that were up to ' in length and engines of sizes F to M They also said that some rockets will reach Now aside from the obvious dangers to any amateur rocketeer using one of these beasts isn't this illegal I can't imagine the FAA allowing people to shoot rockets up through the flight levels of passenger Not to even mention the problem of locating a rocket when it comes And no I'm not going to even think of buying I'm not that Paul mine'll do feet and carries pounds of dynamite Dokas Could it be Public Missile Inc in Michigan From the description of ad here it sounds like they're talking about High Power Rocketry an outgrowth of model This hobby uses non metallic structural compoments and commerically manufactured engines ranging in impulse classification from G to The hobby has been flourishing from early and is becoming increasing Technically this is not consider amateur Any rocket with a liftoff weight greater than pounds OR using a total impulse of G or greater REQUIRES an FAA waiver to Typically a group of people get an FAA waiver for specified period of time ie week weekend at a designated site and time and all of the launches are then covered under this blanket waiver There is also a High Power Safety Code which designates more specific rules such as launch field size Finally in order to purchase any of the larger Class B rocket motors you need to certified through either the National Association of Rocketry or Tripoli Rocketry Certification procedures require a demonstarted handling and safe flight at a total impulse For more information watch Michael Jungclas UUCP att ihlpb rjungcla AT T Bell Labs Naperville Internet